I wake up, stretching and then recoiling from the sharp pain in my groin. "Damn hockey," I grumble. I remember something might be coming today. Something important. I run down the stairs and look out the front window, trying to peer on the porch step. No sign of anything. Sighing, I get dressed and put on shoes to get the mail. As I reach for the front door, I stop dead in my tracks. A brown package, addressed to myself, sitting on the step. I shriek with joy, and fling open the front door only long enough to grab the parcel. My cat watches my commotion with her usual curiousity as I plop down on the couch with a knife to open the box. My hands are shaking, heart beating fast, I rip through the tape into a world of newspaper and stryofoam. Runt moves to sit on my lap, knowing she'll have full priviledges over the empty box. Ripping through the paper I see a hint of orange-yellow through a thick layer of bubble wrap. I can't see anything but the bubble wrap I'm tearing through and the yellow plastic underneath.
